				</div>
				<div type="textpart" n="B"><head xml:lang="eng">Plates</head>
<p>
<!-- argr shall we try to divide into more p's?  -->
<pb n="1v"/><!-- 
This is not explicitly stated anywhere I've read, but I assume that these double plates, each inscribed on one face only, use 1verso and 2 recto, with the blank side of each plate facing outward. 
argr: Fleet (CII 3 p. 106) states explicitly that such is the case
--><lb n="1"/>namo mahādevāya<g type="ddanda">.</g> svasty<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> 
<!-- argr: I'd vote to remove this insertion -->
eka-navaty-uttare 'bda-<space type="binding-hole"/>śate gupta-nr̥pa-rājya-bhuktau śrīmati pravarddhamāna-<!-- 
The punctuation sign is a double vertical, a regular pair of daṇḍas, unlike IN00078. 
--><lb n="2"/>mahā-caittra-sa<sic>mb</sic>atsare 
<!-- argr: I'd vote to remove use of sic here -->
māgha-māsa-bahula-pa<space type="binding-hole"/>kṣa-tr̥tīyāyām<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> 
<!-- argr: I'd vote to remove this insertion -->
asyā<unclear>ṁ</unclear> sa<sic>mb</sic>atsara-
<!-- argr: I'd vote to remove use of sic here -->
māsa-divasa-pūrvvā<lb 
n="3" break="no"/>yāṁ nr̥pati-parivrājaka-kulotpannena mahārāja-devāḍhya-pranaptrā mahārāja-śrī-prabhaṁjana-naptrā mahā<lb 
n="4" break="no"/>rāja-śrī-dāmodara-sutena go-sahasra-hasty-aśva-hiraṇyāneka-bhūmi-pradena guru-pitr̥-mātr̥-pūjā<lb 
n="5" break="no"/>-tatpareṇātyanta-deva-vrāhmaṇa-bhaktenāneka-samara-śata-vijayinā sva-vaṁśāmoda-kareṇa mahā<lb 
n="6" break="no"/>rāja-śrī-hastinā mahādevi-devasukha-vijñaptyā vālugartto 
<!-- argr: I think I see -garttā and we seem to have more cases where the form is explicitly feminine than those where is seems to be masc/ntr -->
nāma grāmaḥ pūrvvāghāṭa-pariccheda-ma<!-- 
Fleet treats Mahādevideva as a name and translates "at the agreeable request of Mahâdêvidêva". But compare l8, for which Fleet translates "in order to erect the steps of a ladder leading to heaven, acceptable to Mahâdêvidêva," ignoring both the feminine and the fact that āropayati doesn't really mean "erect". It seems certain to me that we are dealing with a queen named Devasukhā here (rather than "a certain person named Mahâdêvidêva" [Fleet_1888:107]), and the composer of the charter felt that the proper forms in compound were °devi and °sukha. Finally, compare the almost identical phrasing in IN00081, l12, which Fleet himself translates as I would expect. 
argr: I'd votre for normalizing or correcting i/a to ī/ā (and perhaps also i to ī) — cf.  'caṭa-, -devasukhāṁ and mibhya  below
--><lb n="7" break="no"/>ryādayā 
<!-- argr: ryā is written with subscript y below r -->
sodraṅgaḥ soparikaro ’c<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>ṭa-bhaṭa-prāveśyaḥ mātā-pittror ātmanaś ca puṇyābhivr̥ddhaye mahāde<lb 
n="8" break="no"/>vi-devasukhāṁ ca svargga-sopāna-paṅktim āropayatā Aupamanyava-sagotrebhyaś chandoga-kauthuma<lb 
n="9" break="no"/>-sabrahmacāribhyo <choice><sic>mibhya</sic><corr>'mībhyo</corr></choice> 
<!-- argr I think this should  be m<choice><sic>i</sic><corr>ī</corr></choice>bhychoice><sic>a</sic><corr>o</corr></choice> — or might this rather be intended as evamādibhyo, as in IN00078? — or is it to be expunged as superfluous, perhaps anticipating [devasvā]mibhyaḥ?-->
brāhmaṇebhyaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> 
<!-- argr we have not inserted punctuation in previous cases where sandhi was not applied. why do it now? -->
govindasvāmi<g type="dash">.</g> gomikasvāmi <space/> devasvāmibhyaḥ 
putra-pau<!-- 
Fleet prints gomikasvāmi as in cpd to devasvāmi and emends to add govindasvāmi to the beginning of this cpd, which is of course grammatically fine, but evidently the composer treated compounds more loosely, and there is a distinct space after gomikasvāmi, which must have been intended, just like the dash after the first name, to clearly demarcate the items in the list. 
-->
<!-- argr shall we remove spaces and insert hyphens between the items? -->
<lb n="10" break="no"/>trānvayopabhogyas tāmra-śāsanenāgrahāro
<!-- argr: clearly -āgrahāro and this is what Fleet read  -->
 'tisr̥ṣṭaḥ caura-varjjaM<!-- 
For cora-varjjam (also sic in l13 of IN00077) compare cora-daṇḍa-varjjam in l14 of the Khoh Plate of Jayanātha GE 177, so this means in pursuit of thieves. 
--><!-- 
The halanta m is slightly reduced in size and simplified, and has a horizontal stroke above it. 
-->
<!-- argr represent as M or m·? --></p>
<p>tad asmat-kulotthair mmat-pāda<lb 
n="11" break="no"/>-piṇḍopajīvibhir vvā kālāntareṣv api na vyāghātaḥ karaṇīyaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied>
<!-- argr remove insertion or encode otherwise? -->
 Evam <choice><sic>ājñāpte</sic><corr>ājñapte</corr></choice>
<!-- argr to be encoded otherwise -->
 yo 'nyathā 
<lb n="22"/><!-- argr to be corrected to 12 — ryā written as above-->
kuryāt tam ahaṁ dehāntara-gato 'pi mahatāvaddhyānena nirddaheyam<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> 
<!-- argr remove insertion? may be new p instead? -->
uktaṁ ca bhagavatā parama<pb n="2r" break="no"/><lb 
n="13" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">r</supplied>ṣ<supplied reason="lost">i</supplied>ṇā veda-vyāsena vyāsena||<!-- 
The punctuation sign is again a double vertical (as all others transcribed as double daṇḍas). 
--></p>
<lg n="1" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">pūrvva-dattāṁ dvijātibhyo</l>
<l n="b">yatnād rakṣa yudhiṣṭhira</l>
<l n="c">mahī<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> <lb n="14"/>mahimatāṁ śreṣṭha</l>
<l n="d">dānāc chreyo nupālanaṁ|</l>
</lg>
<lg n="2" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">vahubhir vvasudhā bhuktā</l>
<l n="b">rājabhiḥ sagarādibhiḥ</l>
<l n="c">ya<lb n="15" break="no"/>sya yasya yadā bhūmis</l>
<l n="d">tasya tasya tadā phalaṁ<!-- 
There was a dash at the end of the previous verse, but only a bit of space after this one. 
--></l>
</lg>
<lg n="3" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">ṣaṣṭiṁ varṣa-sahasr<unclear>ā</unclear>ṇi</l>
<l n="b">svargge modati bhūmidaḥ</l>
<l n="c"><lb n="16"/>Ākṣeptā cānumantā ca</l>
<l n="d">tāny eva narake vaseT<!-- 
Again no punctuation, only a halanta character and a little space. 
--><!-- 
The halanta t seems to be full or almost full size, but with a line above. 
--></l>
</lg>
<lg n="4" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">sva-dattāṁ para-dattām <sic>b</sic>ā</l>
<l n="b">yo hareta vasundharāM</l><!-- 
The halanta m is again simplified but almost full size, with a line above. 
-->
<l n="c"><lb n="17"/>sa viṣṭhāyāṁ <sic>kkri</sic>mir bhūtvā</l>
<l n="d">pitr̥bhiḥ saha majjate<!-- 
No punctuation, only a little space at the end of the verse. 
--></l>
</lg>
<lg n="5" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">apānīyeṣv araṇyeṣu</l>
<l n="b">śuṣka-koṭara-vāsinaḥ</l>
<l n="c"><lb n="18"/>kr̥ṣnāhayo bhijāyante</l>
<l n="d">pūrvva-dāyaṁ haranti ye||</l>
</lg>
<p>likhitañ ca vakkrāmātya-pranaptr̥-naptrā<!-- 
Fleet notes that pranaptr̥-naptrā should be understood as naptr̥-naptrā or pranaptr̥-putreṇa, otherwise there would be a missing generation. This is correct; also compare IN00078/29. 
--><lb n="19"/>bhogika-naradatta-pranaptrā ravidatta-naptrā sūryadatta-puttreṇa mahā- sāndhiviggrahika<lb n="20" break="no"/>-vibhudatteneti<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> mahāvalādhikr̥ta-nāgasi<sic>ṅ</sic>ho dūtakaḥ</p>
<p>sambat <num value="191"><g type="numeral">100</g> <g type="numeral">90</g> 1</num><lb n="21"/>māgha di <num value="3">3</num></p>
